+### ūüďĆ Fixed Maximum Temperature
+The maximum safe temperature (TjMax) is read once when your computer starts up. If your BIOS (computer settings) tells it the wrong number, all readings will be wrong forever.
 
- No time-smoothing
-Each read is independent. A 1ms burst gives same weight as sustained load. The value can jump 10¬įC in one tick.
-TjMax is static (read once at boot)
-Stored at init time, never re-read. If BIOS reports wrong TjMax (your E8500 has known issues with this), every reading is offset by that error forever.
-DTS quantisation = 1¬įC steps
-The MSR register stores integers only. Real temp can be 63.7¬įC but you'll see 63 or 64. No sub-degree precision possible from this path.
-No thermal mass modelling
-Silicon has thermal inertia ‚ÄĒ it takes time to heat/cool. coretemp reports the DTS snapshot with zero physics model applied.
-No fan feedback
-Fan RPM is read by a completely separate hwmon driver. coretemp never sees it ‚ÄĒ the two values are never fused.
+### 1ÔłŹ‚É£ Only Whole Degree Precision
+The temperature is stored as whole numbers only. So if the real temperature is 63.7¬įC, you'll only see 63 or 64¬įC on your screen.
 
